04434nam a22005415i 9780300213256DE-B159720200229105050.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200229t20152015ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002132567 a10.12987/97803002132562doi  a(DE-B1597)540342  a(OCoLC)900943251  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aBIO0060002bisacsh04a995.7/12231 aFairhead, James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Captain and "the Cannibal" :bAn Epic Story of Exploration, Kidnapping, and the Broadway Stage /cJames Fairhead. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (392 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Directions in Narrative History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue -- tChapter 1: The Island -- tChapter 2: The Captain -- tChapter 3: At Sea -- tChapter 4: The "Cannibal Show" -- tChapter 5: The Tour -- tChapter 6: The Books -- tChapter 7: Dako, God, and Humanity -- tChapter 8: Fame -- tChapter 9: Return to Dako's Island -- tChapter 10: Missing -- tChapter 11: Tables Turned -- tChapter 12: Sydney Respite -- tChapter 13: Dako's Dominion -- tChapter 14: Shipwreck -- tChapter 15: Morrell Adrift -- tChapter 16: Father and Son -- tChapter 17: The Lost Colony -- tEpilogue: "The Cannibal" and the Captain -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe astounding saga of an American sea captain and the New Guinean nobleman who became his stunned captive, then ally, and eventual friend Sailing in uncharted waters of the Pacific in 1830, Captain Benjamin Morrell of Connecticut became the first outsider to encounter the inhabitants of a small island off New Guinea. The contact quickly turned violent, fatal cannons were fired, and Morrell abducted young Dako, a hostage so shocked by the white complexions of his kidnappers that he believed he had been captured by the dead. This gripping book unveils for the first time the strange odyssey the two men shared in ensuing years. The account is uniquely told, as much from the captive's perspective as from the American's.   Upon returning to New York, Morrell exhibited Dako as a "cannibal" in wildly popular shows performed on Broadway and along the east coast. The proceeds helped fund a return voyage to the South Pacific-the captain hoping to establish trade with Dako's assistance, and Dako seizing his chance to return home with the only person who knew where his island was. Supported by rich, newly found archives, this wide-ranging volume traces the voyage to its extraordinary ends and en route decrypts Morrell's ambiguous character, the mythic qualities of Dako's life, and the two men's infusion into American literature-as Melville's Queequeg, for example, and in Poe's Pym. The encounters confound indigenous peoples and Americans alike as both puzzle over what it is to be truly human and alive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Feb 2020) 0aFirst contact of aboriginal peoples with WesternerszPapua New GuineaxHistoryy19th century. 0aIndigenous peopleszPapua New GuineavBiography. 0aKidnappingzPapua New GuineaxHistoryy19th century. 0aShip captainszConnecticutvBiography. 0aSideshowszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy19th century. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2014-2015z978311067250340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300213256423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300213256.jpg  a978-3-11-067250-3  YUP eBook Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aEBA_FAO